But the question would count anything half-assed as the middle option, and I figure it's quite possible that there will be some half-measure (more likely quarter- or tenth-measure) signed. That's because: a) Trump is willful, b) he likes wins (even if he doesn't like working for them, or making them meaningful), c) congressional republicans are very good at obeying the party line, once there is one, d) democrats have been surprisingly eager to cave on this issue so far, and e) democrats run the risk of getting blamed if they don't take some crumbs, and f) DACA folks don't like being used, and could ruin democrats image on this.

The poor performance of the President's proposal among Senate Republicans has rendered it moot as a battering ram to use against "vulnerable" Democrats, and it is difficult to see a veto-proof majority coalescing around anything more narrowly-focused (assuming that the President does not change course again). Democrats, meanwhile, know that DACA recipients do not all become vulnerable to deportation at once, even in the absence of legislation. This will be a game of attrition, with Democrats making the most of every sympathetic case leading into the midterms.
